711029f-a.text:
101-11 West 10th Street (formerly 1-11 Amos Street), at and adjoining N.W. corner of Sixth Avenue. There are old frame houses which were later refaced with brick. The drug store on the corner will be succeeded about 1929 by a lunch room, and the building will be remodelled downstairs so as to put the stairs on the western end, making more room for the restaurant. The shoe repair shop will go out of business at that time or earlier. Notice the law and bail bond offices; Jefferson Market Court is situated on the south-west corner, right across the street.
This street, which is parallel with Christopher, Charles, and Perry Streets, happens to coincide at the point with the western end of Amos Street was dropped, and the street later renumbered as an extension of West 10th Street, 100 being added to the Amos Street numbers.

February, 1922.
Gift of K. M. Jenks.

709341f-a.text:
Sixth Avenue, at, adjoining and north of the N.W. corner of West 10th Street, showing a triangular nest of small buildings incorporating Mulligan and Patchin Places. The former is to the fore and is entered upon from Sixth Avenue, between No's 451 and 453 (old No's. 139 and 141). This detail is clearest in View 2. Patchin Place is at the rear and opens on West 1Oth Street. Note a partial glimpse of the Jefferson Market Court on the left. The Sixth Avenue Elevated shown, will be razed in 1939.
May 30, 1929
Views 1, 2
P. L. Sperr

711027f-a.text:
55-43 West 10th Street, north side, just east of Sixth Avenue. No (old No. 15, 10th Street), with the Bell Telephone sign on the stoop is the Tenth Street Studios, Incorporated, the first building to devoted entirely and primarily to artists' studios. St Gaudens and John LaFarge, among other notable artists, have maintained studios in it. Built in 1857 at old 13-21 10th Street (10th Street was numbered east from Sixth Avenue), it will still be standing in 1935.
About 1923.
Gift of E. N. Jenks.                  Neg. # 570
Slide # 137
